(95, 1, '2013-04-22 10:32:32', '2013-04-22 10:32:32', '', 'Electronic Health Records: Audit and Internal Control', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'electronic-health-records-audit-and-internal-control', '', '', '2013-04-25 06:54:28', '2013-04-25 06:54:28', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/?p=95', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(96, 1, '2013-04-22 10:32:31', '2013-04-22 10:32:31', '', 'Electronic Health Records: Audit and Internal Control', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '95-revision', '', '', '2013-04-22 10:32:31', '2013-04-22 10:32:31', '', 95, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/95-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(98, 1, '2013-04-22 10:48:25', '2013-04-22 10:48:25', 'When Willie Sutton, an infamous twentieth-century bank robber, was asked why he robbed banks, he replied, “Because that’s where the money is.’’ The healthcare industry, too, has lots of money – estimated to be a $2.9 trillion industry in 2009. How many of these annual healthcare dollars are attributed to fraud? About $25 million per hour is stolen in healthcare in the United States alone. This course is designed to introduce the healthcare industry: a highly segmented market with high-dollar cash transactions from a fraud audit and detection perspective. This course also teaches “what is normal” in the marketplace so that abnormalities become apparent. Healthcare fraud prevention, detection, and investigation methods are outlined, as are internal controls and anomaly tracking systems for ongoing monitoring and surveillance. The ultimate goal is to help people see beyond the eclipse created by healthcare fraud and sharpen audit and investigation skills to identify incontrovertible truth.', 'Introduction to Healthcare Fraud Auditing and Detection', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'introduction-to-healthcare-fraud-auditing-and-detection', '', '', '2013-04-22 10:48:25', '2013-04-22 10:48:25', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/?post_type=question&#038;p=98', 0, 'question', '', 0),
(99, 1, '2013-04-22 10:48:42', '2013-04-22 10:48:42', 'To understand, detect, and prevent healthcare fraud, it is important to understand healthcare’s market participants. This course introduces the concept of the healthcare continuums, including the Primary, Secondary, Information, Consequence and Transparency Healthcare Continuums. Specific fraud schemes within each market segment are also introduced.', 'Defining Market Participants', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'defining-market-participants', '', '', '2013-04-22 10:48:42', '2013-04-22 10:48:42', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/?post_type=question&#038;p=99', 0, 'question', '', 0),
(100, 1, '2013-04-22 10:48:59', '2013-04-22 10:48:59', 'A commonality among all market participants is the use of patients’ protected health information (PHI) (also called identifiable protected health information, or IPHI). The use of PHI among fraud schemes is also common. Access to PHI is key, both for those who perpetuate fraud schemes and for those who act as gatekeepers or damage-control experts. A fine line exists between PHI access and privacy and potential defrauders are eager to cross this line. This course is designed to explore PHI, its use and the audit implications of HIPAA.', 'HIPAA and Protected Health Information Audit Implication', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hipaa-and-protected-health-information-audit-implication', '', '', '2013-04-22 10:48:59', '2013-04-22 10:48:59', '', 0, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/?post_type=question&#038;p=100', 0, 'question', '', 0),
(101, 1, '2013-04-22 10:32:04', '2013-04-22 10:32:04', '', 'Healthcare Fraud Auditing and Detection', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '93-revision-2', '', '', '2013-04-22 10:32:04', '2013-04-22 10:32:04', '', 93, 'http://192.168.1.220:8086/mbt/93-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
